{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-access-the-spark-ui-without-setting-up-a-spark-history-server-674570880aac", "time": 1683017612.827735, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-to-access-the-spark-ui-without-setting-up-a-spark-history-server-674570880aac/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How to access the Spark UI without setting up a Spark History Server | by Jean Yves | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to access the Spark UI without setting up a Spark History Server", "description": "Using Delight, an open-source monitoring tool for Apache Spark that replaces the Spark UI and Spark History Server, and works on top of any Spark platform."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/web-ui.html", "anchor_text": "Spark UI", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.datamechanics.co/apache-spark", "anchor_text": "Apache Spark", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/monitoring.html#viewing-after-the-fact", "anchor_text": "Spark History Server", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://www.datamechanics.co/delight", "anchor_text": "Data Mechanics Delight", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://github.com/datamechanics/delight", "anchor_text": "github", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://www.datamechanics.co/blog-post/delight-the-new-improved-spark-ui-spark-history-server-is-now-ga", "anchor_text": "Delight has now been officially released", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://github.com/datamechanics/delight/blob/main/documentation/resources/example_spark_event_log_message.json", "anchor_text": "view a sample event", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://www.datamechanics.co/blog-post/building-a-better-spark-ui-data-mechanics-delight", "anchor_text": "June 2020 announcement to learn more about the vision behind Delight", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://www.datamechanics.co/apache-spark-on-kubernetes", "anchor_text": "Spark on Kubernetes", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://www.datamechanics.co/blog-post/delight-the-new-improved-spark-ui-spark-history-server-is-now-ga", "anchor_text": "officially released", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://www.datamechanics.co", "anchor_text": "Data Mechanics", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "http://Spot.io", "anchor_text": "Spot.io", "paragraph_index": 10}], "all_paragraphs": ["For \u201clive\u201d Spark applications, accessing the Spark UI \u2014 the open-source monitoring interface of Apache Spark \u2014 is easy, as it is served directly by the Spark driver on port 4040.", "But once an application has completed, accessing the Spark UI requires setting up a Spark History Server, which takes a bit of work. In this article, we\u2019re going to show you how to access the Spark UI for completed Spark applications with very little effort by leveraging a free open-source monitoring project called Data Mechanics Delight (see the github page).", "Update(April 2021): Delight has now been officially released!", "The agent collects your Spark applications event metrics. This is non-sensitive information about the metadata of your Spark application. For example, for each Spark task there is metadata on memory usage, CPU usage, network traffic (view a sample event). The agent does not record sensitive information such as the data that your Spark applications actually work on. The agent does *not* collect your application logs either \u2014 as typically they may contain sensitive information.", "This data is encrypted using your personal access token and sent over the internet using the HTTPS protocol. This information is then stored securely behind an authentication layer. Only you (and your colleagues, if you signed up with your company\u2019s google account) will be able to see your application in our dashboard. The collected data will automatically be deleted 30 days after your Spark application completion.", "The release of this freely hosted dashboard and Spark History Server is but the first step towards replacing the Spark UI entirely by a more user-friendly interface display new metrics (memory, cpu, I/O) and visualizations. Read our June 2020 announcement to learn more about the vision behind Delight.", "While the current release does not yet replace the Spark UI, we hope it will be valuable to some of you, particularly the Spark on Kubernetes users (as running the SHS on k8s requires a lot of setup and ).", "Update (April 2021): Delight has now been officially released! For each application it features an overview screen display CPU & Memory Metrics to make it more easy to troubleshoot the performance of your Spark applications!", "Our mission at Data Mechanics is to make Spark much more developer-friendly and cost-effective. We hope this tool will be useful to you!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Co-Founder @Data Mechanics, The Cloud-Native Spark Platform Senior Product Manager @ Spot.io \u2014 Building Ocean for Spark Former software eng @Databricks."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F674570880aac&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-access-the-spark-ui-without-setting-up-a-spark-history-server-674570880aac&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-access-the-spark-ui-without-setting-up-a-spark-history-server-674570880aac&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav---------------------